attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2, for GNU/Linux 2.6.18, BuildID[sha1]=8ebe1377890128b4ebe1d16ae0f2dd267aa53dfc, stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This is a backdoor trojan that masquerades as a legitimate system service. It daemonizes itself, changes its process name to a common system process name (e.g., '/sbin/udevd -d', '/sbin/mingetty /dev/tty7') to evade detection, and creates a PID file at '/var/run/haldrund.pid' for persistence. The malware uses a raw socket to sniff network traffic for specific trigger packets. Upon receiving a trigger, it can manipulate firewall rules using 'iptables' to open ports or redirect traffic, and ultimately provides a reverse shell by spawning '/bin/sh' and redirecting its I/O over the network, giving an attacker remote control of the system.
